			<unit id="106" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The semantic zoom control enables the user to zoom between two different views of the same content so that they can quickly navigate through a large data set.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="107" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The zoomed-in view is the main view of the content.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="108" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>You show the complete data set in this view.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="109" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>The zoomed-out view is a higher-level view of the same content.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="110" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>You typically show the group headers for a grouped data set in this view.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
			<unit id="111" translate="yes">
				<segment state="initial">
					<source>For example, when viewing an address book, the user could zoom in on a letter and see the names associated with that letter.</source>
				</segment>
			</unit>
